## Summary

**Bug:** In "Hide others" mode, windows came back smaller — on a 4K monitor, Chrome returned shorter (height wrong, width fine).

**Root cause:** The window-level hide-others reveal parks sibling windows off-screen via AX `setPosition` (from Bringr-93j.24), but only captured/restored each window's **position**, not its **size**. When macOS moves a window off the bottom of every screen, `NSWindow`'s title-bar constraint **clamps the window's height** (not width) so it stays reachable — so restoring position alone left the window at the clamped, shorter height.

**Fix:** Capture and restore window size alongside position.
- `WindowControl.swift` — added `size(of:)`/`setSize(_:_:)` to the `WindowControlling` protocol; added `WindowSnapshot.originalSize`; threaded it through `captureWindowBaselineIfNeeded`, `restoreWindowBaseline`, `restoreCapturedFrame` (renamed from `restoreCapturedPosition`), `persistSnapshot`, and `applySnapshot`. Restore order is position-then-size so the window grows from its anchored top-left.
- `LiveWindowSystem.swift` — AX implementations reading/writing `kAXSizeAttribute`.
- `RevealState.swift` — `originalSize` added to the crash-recovery `RevealSnapshot.WindowEntry`.
- Tests — 2 new in `RevealStrategyTests` (restore + re-target), 1 new in `RevealStateTests` (crash recovery), plus a baseline-capture assertion; `FakeWindowSystem` now models window size.

**Quality gates:** `swiftlint lint --strict` 0 violations · build SUCCEEDED · 227 tests pass. App rebuilt, relaunched, and left running (PID 71838). Bead Bringr-93j.28 closed; `progress.md` updated.

Note: I couldn't reproduce the exact macOS height-clamp visually (it needs the off-screen park on a real multi-display setup), but the capture/restore-size logic is a complete fix regardless of the clamp's cause, and is covered by the new unit tests.

